  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2228635492?book_show_action=true">Jan 29, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alex" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alex" href="/user/show/90587-alex">Alex</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2228635492" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9643449618918044860">I&apos;ve always enjoyed Brad Warner&apos;s writing, but I had to read a lot of American Zen writing to appreciate how unlike most American Zen teachers and authors he is, and how important his perspective is. <br/><br/>The vast majority of American-born Zen teachers (especially the ones who write books) began practicing Buddhism in California in the 1960s and 1970s. Their perspective is inevitably, at least to some degree, a product of that cultural moment, and &quot;American Zen&quot;, whatever that is exactly, has become </span>
  <span id="freeText9643449618918044860" style="display:none">I've always enjoyed Brad Warner's writing, but I had to read a lot of American Zen writing to appreciate how unlike most American Zen teachers and authors he is, and how important his perspective is. <br /><br />The vast majority of American-born Zen teachers (especially the ones who write books) began practicing Buddhism in California in the 1960s and 1970s. Their perspective is inevitably, at least to some degree, a product of that cultural moment, and "American Zen", whatever that is exactly, has become difficult to distinguish from the relationship to Zen that this very particular group of people developed. (If you start practicing Zen in formal settings in this country you will pick up on this fairly quickly and some younger practitioners refer to it, with varying degrees of affection, as "Boomer Zen".)<br /><br />I do not mean to say, and do not believe, that all these "Boomer Zen" teachers are a bunch of indistinguishable sheep or that their books are not worth reading. On the contrary, I think this group of people has done an amazing job of articulating and transmitting the core teachings, and of creating practice centers and models of community-based Zen practice that make it very easy to find support in your practice in this country. This should not be taken for granted, and serious students of Zen in this country should be grateful that places like San Francisco Zen Center exist. Students of SFZC and other places have fanned out across the country and started their own groups and now just about any college town or medium-sized city has a place where you can go and find instruction and community. This is an awesome gift.<br /><br />That being said, these older practitioners do have their particular tics and preoccupations. Imagine a white person in their 70s who went to Dartmouth, participated in anti-war demonstrations, has a robust stock portfolio, owns two homes, has an impressive incense and candle collection, has never in their life interacted with a person who voted for Donald Trump, and writes essays in Lion's Roar about making sure to compost and not kill spiders in their summer home. A lot of Boomer Zen writing has this feel to it. (This is of course a caricature intended to make a point.)<br /><br />Brad Warner is not one of these people. Not only is he from a different generation, but he developed his Zen practice in Japan, where he lived and worked for many years, rather than in one of the major Zen training centers in this country (SFZC, Zen Mountain Monastery, Mt. Baldy, etc.). While he is not apolitical, he is not fixated on the same kinds of identity politics and social justice questions that have become almost inseparable from the most prominent voices in American Zen. This is not to say that it is undesirable to have these concerns, but only to make the point that these concerns are not an *inevitable* outcome of Zen practice. I think this is important because Zen Buddhism in the west is extremely young, and I think westerners are still figuring out how to embody it, and having access to diverse expressions of American Zen is probably an important part of developing a collectively mature relationship to Buddhism in our culture.<br /><br />At the same time, he is not some upstart contrarian. At this point he's been practicing and teaching Zen for decades, and is a recognized part of an established lineage of teachers. His writing is relentlessly straightforward and free of bullshit: If you want to practice Zen, you have to stop reading and talking about it and do it (even though reading and talking about it is necessary from time to time). No one else can live your life for you. Anyone who tells you they can give you the answers and solve your problems for you is a fraud. Anyone who claims to be enlightened is a fraud. But his approach as an author/teacher is not just about calling out bullshit. His main focus is to offer realistic, humble, honest practical guidance won through many years of practice. You can see this in both his writing and his online presence. I am not aware of another Zen teacher who devotes so much time to communicating with their readers, answering emails, responding to comments on his YouTube videos (he pretty reliably puts out at least one per week, and has been for a long time), etc. <br /><br />Anyway yeah check out Brad Warner if you want.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9643449618918044860" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


